05610nam a22007935i 9780812202656DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979580239  a97808122026567 a10.9783/97808122026562doi  a(DE-B1597)449121  a(OCoLC)859160677  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a296.3/61 aLobel, Diana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Sufi-Jewish Dialogue :bPhilosophy and Mysticism in Bahya ibn Paquda's "Duties of the Heart" /cDiana Lobel. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Bah̩ya's Work in Its Judeo-Arabic Context -- t1. Philosophical Mysticism in Eleventh-Century Spain: Baḥ'ya and Ibn Gabirol -- t2. On the Lookout The Exegesis of a Sufi Tale -- t3. Creation -- t4. The One -- t5. Speaking about God: Divine Attributes, Biblical Language, and Biblical Exegesis -- t6. The Contemplation of Creation (l'tibār) -- t7. Wholehearted Devotion (lkhlāṣ ): Purification of Unity (lkhlāṣ al-Tawḥi ̄d), Purification of Intention in Action (Ikhlāṣ al-'Amal) -- t8. Reason, Law, and the Way of the Spirit -- t9. The Spirituality of the Law -- t10. Awareness, Love, and Reverence (Murāqaba, Mah̩abba, Hayba/Yir'ah) -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWritten in Judeo-Arabic in eleventh-century Muslim Spain but quickly translated into Hebrew, Bahya Ibn Paquda's Duties of the Heart is a profound guidebook of Jewish spirituality that has enjoyed tremendous popularity and influence to the present day. Readers who know the book primarily in its Hebrew version have likely lost sight of the work's original Arabic context and its immersion in Islamic mystical literature. In A Sufi-Jewish Dialogue, Diana Lobel explores the full extent to which Duties of the Heart marks the flowering of the "Jewish-Arab symbiosis," the interpenetration of Islamic and Jewish civilizations.Lobel reveals Bahya as a maverick who integrates abstract negative theology, devotion to the inner life, and an intimate relationship with a personal God. Bahya emerges from her analysis as a figure so steeped in Islamic traditions that an Arabic reader could easily think he was a Muslim, yet the traditional Jewish seeker has always looked to him as a fountainhead of Jewish devotion. Indeed, Bahya represents a genuine bridge between religious cultures. He brings together, as well, a rationalist, philosophical approach and a strain of Sufi mysticism, paving the way for the integration of philosophy and spirituality in the thought of Moses Maimonides.A Sufi-Jewish Dialogue is the first scholarly book in English about a tremendously influential work of medieval Jewish thought and will be of interest to readers working in comparative literature, philosophy, and religious studies, particularly as reflected in the interplay of the civilizations of the Middle East. Readers will discover an extraordinary time when Jewish, Christian, and Islamic thinkers participated in a common spiritual quest, across traditions and cultural boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJewish ethicsvEarly works to 1800. 0aJudaismvRelationsvIslam. 0aJudaismxRelationsxIslam. 0aSufism. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part o